<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="73" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73">
Usually found immersed in prey sponge 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Johnston" authorityYear="1842" class="Demospongea" family="Dysideidae" genus="Dysidea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Dysidea" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Dysidea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. under rubble and dead fungiid coral skeletons in shallow coral reef habitats. Uncommon, though multiple individuals may be observed together. Depth 3-8 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="73" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73">
Across the western Pacific including Indonesia (
<bibRefCitation author="Yonow, N" journalOrPublisher="Zoologische Mededelingen" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" pagination="1 - 50" publicationUrl="http://www.repository.naturalis.nl/document/45054" refId="B285" refString="Yonow, N, 2001. Results of the Rumphius Biohistorical Expedition to Ambon (1990). Part 11. Doridacea of the families Chromodorididae and Hexabranchidae (Mollusca, Gastropoda, Opisthobranchia, Nudibranchia), including additional Moluccan material. Zoologische Mededelingen 75: 1 - 50, http://www.repository.naturalis.nl/document/45054" title="Results of the Rumphius Biohistorical Expedition to Ambon (1990). Part 11. Doridacea of the families Chromodorididae and Hexabranchidae (Mollusca, Gastropoda, Opisthobranchia, Nudibranchia), including additional Moluccan material." url="http://www.repository.naturalis.nl/document/45054" volume="75" year="2001">Yonow 2001</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/146/135-172" author="Yonow, N" journalOrPublisher="Archiv fuer Molluskenkunde International Journal of Malacology" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" pagination="135 - 172" refId="B290" refString="Yonow, N, 2017. Results of the Rumphius Biohistorical Expedition to Ambon (1990). Part 16. The Nudibranchia - Dendronotina, Arminina, Aeolidina, and Doridina (Mollusca: Gastropoda: Heterobranchia). Archiv fuer Molluskenkunde International Journal of Malacology 146: 135 - 172, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/146/135-172" title="Results of the Rumphius Biohistorical Expedition to Ambon (1990). Part 16. The Nudibranchia - Dendronotina, Arminina, Aeolidina, and Doridina (Mollusca: Gastropoda: Heterobranchia)." url="https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/146/135-172" volume="146" year="2017">2017</bibRefCitation>
), the Philippines, Palau, Papua New Guinea, and Australia (
<bibRefCitation author="Gosliner, TM" journalOrPublisher="Sea Challengers Natural History Books, Gig Harbor" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" refId="B94" refString="Gosliner, TM, Behrens, D, Valdes, A, 2008. Indo-Pacific nudibranchs and sea slugs: a field guide to the world's most diverse fauna. Sea Challengers Natural History Books, Gig Harbor" title="Indo-Pacific nudibranchs and sea slugs: a field guide to the world's most diverse fauna." year="2008">Gosliner et al. 2008</bibRefCitation>
). Recorded from the Gulf of Thailand (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s12526-015-0424-7" author="Mehrotra, R" journalOrPublisher="Marine Biodiversity" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" pagination="761 - 771" refId="B161" refString="Mehrotra, R, Scott, CM, 2016. Species inventory of sea slugs (Gastropoda: Heterobranchia) for Koh Tao, Thailand, with 25 first records for Thai waters. Marine Biodiversity 46: 761 - 771, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/s12526-015-0424-7" title="Species inventory of sea slugs (Gastropoda: Heterobranchia) for Koh Tao, Thailand, with 25 first records for Thai waters." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s12526-015-0424-7" volume="46" year="2016">Mehrotra and Scott 2016</bibRefCitation>
). Very variable in pattern.
</paragraph>
